2026-05-19 | Minimum Multiplications to Reach End

	Question
Return minimum steps required, or -1 if impossible.
	Key Insight
Each number from:
		0 to 999
can be treated as a graph node.
From one node:
		you can move to multiple new nodes
		using multiplication operations.
Since every operation costs 1:
		use BFS for shortest path.
	Approach
1.	Create distance array of size 1000  
2.	Start BFS from start  
3.	For every current value:
		try:
				(current * x) % 1000
		for all x in arr  
4.	If new state not visited:
		update distance
		push into queue
5.	If end reached:
		return steps
	Time Complexity
	O(1000 × size(arr))
	Space Complexity
	O(1000)
	Solution
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumMultiplications(vector<int>& arr,
                               int start,
                               int end) {
        vector<int> dist(1000, -1);
        queue<int> q;
        q.push(start);
        dist[start] = 0;
        while(!q.empty()){
            int curr = q.front();
            q.pop();
            if(curr == end)
                return dist[curr];
            for(int x : arr){
                int next = (curr * x) % 1000;
                if(dist[next] == -1){
                    dist[next] = dist[curr] + 1;
                    q.push(next);
                }
            }
        }
        return -1;
    }
};
	Key Insight
The modulo operation limits states to:
		only 1000 possible numbers  
So BFS efficiently explores all reachable states
and guarantees minimum operations.
